SIMPLE: splice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Splice
<hw>Splice</hw> <pr>(spl⟦imac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spliced</conjf>
<pr>(spl⟦imac⟧st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Splicing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[D.
<ets>splitsen</ets>, <ets>splitten</ets>; akin to G.
<ets>splissen</ets>, Sw. <ets>splissa</ets>, Dan. <ets>splisse</ets>,
and E. <ets>split</ets>; -- from the dividing or splitting the ends into
separate strands. See <er>Split</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To unite, as two ropes, or parts of a rope, by a
particular manner of interweaving the strands, -- the union being
between two ends, or between an end and the body of a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite, as spars, timbers, rails, etc., by lapping
the two ends together, or by applying a piece which laps upon the two
ends, and then binding, or in any way making fast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To unite in marriage.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Splice grafting</b></col>.<cd>ee under
<er>Grafting</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To splice the main brace</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to give out, or drink, an extra allowance of
spirits on occasion of special exposure to wet or cold, or to severe
fatigue; hence, to take a dram.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Splice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Splice
<hw>Splice</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A junction or joining made by
splicing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spline</ent>⟦br⟧
